Once a year the Wodaabe people from across the country come together for the Gerewol gathering, a celebration of beauty and courtship that has been taking place for hundreds of years. For eight days I witnessed young men with brightly painted faces, wearing colourful clothing and jewelry, dance in line, singing and chanting, in the hope of being selected by a lover. The ultimate celebration of beauty and connection. A distinctive aspect of the event is the way the men show the whiteness of their eyes and teeth to display their strength and good health. The chant they make by vibrating their lips is inspired by the egret, a bird the Wodaabe associate with charisma and eloquence. Every year these groups would reconnect and discuss crops, livestock, weather and expectations for the year to come. . 
Wodaabe | Gerewol festival, Bossio, Chari-Baguirmi region | Chad | 2016 .

I first visited Tibet in late 1980 on my initial solo journey into the wonderful culturally diverse world that has now become my life. I was deeply affected by the Tibetan Buddhist tradition. I was touched by the daily, if not an hourly practice of all peoples. Tibetans spend much of their time in prayer or spinning prayer wheels, which is believed to be almost as spiritually meritorious an activity as prayer. Like all Buddhists, Tibetans adhere to non-violence, do good deeds, present gifts to monks and aspire to have gentle thoughts essentially at all times. This hourly, daily, weekly, ritual is the essence of their existence and still, today plays an important part in my life. . 
Buddhist Monks | Ganden Monastery | Tibet | 2011 .

I am often asked what my favorite places are on the planet. Although generally, this is a very difficult question to answer, I do have a very soft spot for Vanuatu. An archipelago of 83 Islands set deep in the South pacific. I fondly remember my first visit to the island of Tanna and staying in the village of Yakel. The experience was made even more intense by the fact that all the villagers were preparing for the 3 days Toka Festival. A festival to symbolize an alliance and friendship between different tribal groups. During this gift-exchanging ceremony, up to 2,000 participants attempt to outdo each other with their lavish gifts, dancing skills, and ornate make-up. . 
Big Nambas| Vanuatu | 2011 .

A number of years ago, whilst photographing Before They Pass Away, I had the privilege to attend “El Día de la Tradición”. Argentinians gather annually to celebrate being a Gaucho and the culture and rural life around this. This festive is being held in the town of San Antonio de Areco since 1939 after José Hernández wrote the famous epic poem “Martín Fierro” in which the Gaucho symbolizes the Argentinean national tradition. During the festival, there are parades, dances and musical performances, and traditional skills which are displayed under a cloud of Barbeque smoke and evocative tango music. The 3-day experience is like stepping back in time, never to be forgotten. I still dream of one day riding off across the Argentinian Pampas leaving a dust of smoke behind dressed in all the silver pride of the Gaucho culture. .  Gauchos | Argentina | 2011 . 
#HomageToHumanity #JimmyNelson #AllHuman #JoinJimmy #photography #culture #culturaldiversity #unitedindiversity #seethebiggerpicture #travel #Argentina

As the year 2019 is drawing to a close, we are gathering our loved ones around us to consolidate and celebrate the year that has passed and wait with bated breath for the new year to come. On all my journeys over the years it has always been the Festive Gatherings which have provided the richest experience and provided the most colourful record. I love the Himalayas so I visit regularly. When I visited the Kingdom of Lo Mustang In Nepal for the annual Tiji Festival I was blessed to witness one of the last true gatherings and celebrations of Ancient Tibetan Wisdom and Custom. This 3-day event at the end of every year is a riot of colour. During the festive, all the monks from the kingdom gather to ward off the Demons and evil spirits to path a safe and healthy path for the future. On the last evening, I was honoured to be included in the closing ceremony and was taken deep into the womb of the Soul of this ancient ritual. . 
Mustang | Nepal | 2011 .

Stephanie: “From sunrise to sunset we film the Muchimba mothers and their children, following them back and forth across the dunes. We are both overwhelmed by the warmth, both human and physical. On our departure, we are clasped in endless embraces and cuddles. We will never forget this trip, and the ochre stains on our clothes will be a welcome reminder for a long time to come. Thank you for showing and sharing with us such beauty and love!” @stephanievdwiel

Muchimba | Cunene province | Angola 2017
.

“Light” - a poem by Rabindranath Tagore.

Light, my light, the world-filling light,
the eye-kissing light,
heart-sweetening light!

Ah, the light dances, my darling, at the center of my life;
the light strikes, my darling, the chords of my love;
the sky opens, the wind runs wild, laughter passes over the earth.

The butterflies spread their sails on the sea of light.
Lilies and jasmines surge up on the crest of the waves of light.

The light is shattered into gold on every cloud, my darling,
and it scatters gems in profusion.

Mirth spreads from leaf to leaf, my darling,
and gladness without measure.
The heaven's river has drowned its banks
and the flood of joy is abroad.
.

Muchimba | Hartmann Valley, Cafema | Namibia 2015
.

Have things changed for your community in your lifetime?” Stephanie asks. “Our traditions are changing fast. About ten years ago young people started wearing Western clothes. We don’t have a television but we see other people wearing modern clothes. That’s always the catalyst. If I find a man I want to be with and he likes my traditional clothing, I’ll be able to keep dressing like this, in the old way. If he doesn’t like my traditional clothing, I’ll start wearing Western clothing too. The men are changing from traditional to modern dress. Men can just wear what they want, but they don’t approve of us doing the same”. @stephanievdwiel
.

Muchimba | Cuene province | Angola 2017
.
#HomageToHumanity #JimmyNelson #AllHuman #JoinJimmy #photography #culture #culturaldiversity #seethebiggerpicture #unitedindiversity #travel #Angola

“We use ochre not only for our skin but for our hair too. We rub the wet paste into our hair to make long braids. A few times a year we wash it all out and redo it. If there’s a special occasion coming up we put on more ochre. It’s a kind of make-up. The longer strands aren’t our own hair: we buy them and weave them in.”
.
Muchimba | Cunene province | Angola 2017
.

How the Himbas manage to blend so effortlessly in with the natural environment is spellbinding. The golden evening light shafts through the roof of their house as they communally prepare the evening meal. It is a widely held myth outside the community that local people believe a Muchimba man cannot build a house and that only his wife can build it for him. As well as the adobe other types of houses are built from a similar clay base topped with a thatched roof.
.
Muchimba | Hartmann Valley, Cafema | Namibia 2015
.

A photographic portrait strives to capture poetry in a painting. We seek to capture a likeness, but a likeness alone (however accurate) is not enough. The best portraits seem to be possessed by their people. Their power, vigor, dignity, and pride are not merely reflected but enacted every time one poses for the camera to paint the scene.
.
Mwila | Chibia region | Angola 2017
.

The Epupa Falls flows from the Cunene River on the border of Angola and Namibia, in the Kaokoland area of the Kunene Region. The river is 0.5 km wide and drops in a series of waterfalls spread over 1.5 km, with the greatest single drop being 37 meters which creates a spectacular backdrop to photograph the Himba and their proud stature.
.
Muchimba | Hartmann Valley, Cafema | Namibia 2015
.

It’s beautiful to watch within these communities how early on the girls want to associate themselves with their culture. They are not necessarily required to wear these necklaces until they have become a woman. But long before they reach puberty these young girls were already gathering their collections.
.

When making initial contact with the communities, we not only try to connect ourselves but make sure that they make connections with one another. The best way to do this is to ask to hold one another. This also has the advantage of building a stronger aesthetic picture as every hand tells another life story.
.
Mwila | Chibia region | Angola 2017 .

I love watching these communities. There is a lot of time spend on preening and grooming each other. This mother is grooming her daughter and explaining to her that prior to becoming a woman, she has to wear the braids over her face. Yet come that day, the braids come loose, drape down her back and she can cover them in mud accordingly. Then she becomes a Himba woman.
.
Himba | Hartmann Valley, Cafema | Namibia 2015
.

The majority of the portraits we make are essentially set up in a studio: a controlled light setting where we use reflectors to redirect the ambient light. Yet sometimes on very rare occasions a spontaneous look, moment or image emerges and a fragile beauty unfolds before the camera: a mother delicately plating the hair of her patient child.
.
Himba | Hartmann Valley, Cafema | Namibia 2015
.
#HomageToHumanity #JimmyNelson #AllHuman #JoinJimmy #photography #culture #culturaldiversity #seethebiggerpicture #unitedindiversity #travel #Namibia #Angola

When evening falls we settle down with the villagers. While enjoying our repetitive dinner of white rice and gravy, the chief tells us some tragic stories about the long war in Angola. ‘As you can see, we are very peaceful people now. We are tired of the violence. Twenty million landmines were buried around the country, and most of them are still there, and being found daily causing horrific injuries. Angola was the most mined country after Vietnam.’ With this reminder of Angola’s dark past, we let the nightfall to a distant chorus of barking dogs, crying babies, chirping crickets, and snoring neighbours as we all lay our heads down under the blanket of stars. The Angolan Civil War lasted for roughly 26 years, between 1975 and 2002. It started immediately after a power vacuum was created by the withdrawal of the colonial power Portugal. Otherworld powers immediately moved in to start greedily fighting over the nation’s rich and untapped mineral resources. The traces of the Angolan Civil War are still to be found today as the whole of the nation is littered with war wreckage. Angola has still today the largest abundance of undiscovered land mines.
.
Himba | Hartmann Valley, Cafema | Namibia 2015
.
#HomageToHumanity #JimmyNelson #AllHuman #JoinJimmy #photography #culture #culturaldiversity #seethebiggerpicture #unitedindiversity #travel #Namibia #Angola

She Walks in Beauty - LORD BYRON.
“She walks in beauty, like the night
Of cloudless climes and starry skies;
And all that’s best of dark and bright
Meet in her aspect and her eyes;
Thus mellowed to that tender light
Which heaven to gaudy day denies.

One shade the more, one ray the less,
Had half impaired the nameless grace
Which waves in every raven tress,
Or softly lightens o’er her face;
Where thoughts serenely sweet express,
How pure, how dear their dwelling-place.

And on that cheek, and o’er that brow,
So soft, so calm, yet eloquent,
The smiles that win, the tints that glow,
But tell of days in goodness spent,
A mind at peace with all below,
A heart whose love is innocent!
.
Mwila | Chibia region | Angola 2017 .

Every image is subjective. Every photograph and painting that has ever been made is from the perspective of the maker. However, what is important to understand is the message behind the artist. What is he or she trying to communicate through the images being made and presented?  What I, as an artist, am saying is that the communities I visually represent are as rich as we are, as powerful as we are, and as dignified as we are. In the “developed” world, when we look at a glossy magazine, we never question the illustration of this subjective aspirational beauty. Yet as soon as the same light is shone on indigenous people who are generally perceived as primitive and poor and backward we question it. Why? Surely it is just the same light of inspiration we shine on ourselves. I feel it may be the fact that it makes us feel uncomfortable to realize, after all this time, endlessly pursuing a material dream of success and happiness. It may have been staring us in the face all along. The daunting realization that we humans in the developed world may be ignoring the essence of being, balance, and purpose. That of being proudly at one with ourselves, one another our traditions and the natural world. Therefore, I aspire as an artist to shine a light of beauty on all others as a mirror to reassess ourselves. Join the discussion.
.
#HomageToHumanity #JimmyNelson #AllHuman #JoinJimmy #photography #culture #culturaldiversity #unitedindiversity #seethebiggerpicture #representation #representativeothers

In some parts of the world, traditional attire is only worn during ceremonial events. However, in other parts of the world, traditional clothing is worn constantly. Sometimes because it has a functional aspect or other times as with the Chukchi in North-Eastern Siberia of Chukotka because it's so cold and the reindeer fur is the only practical way to keep warm. Here in this harsh environment, you see Oxana and her mother Oleasya huddled tight warm bathed in the light of the fire. They are traditionally dressed with their coats made of reindeer skin fur.
.
Chukchi, Oxana Teyunrultett & Oleasya Etguest | Chukotka | Russia | 2012
.
